It takes me 20-25 minutes to get to the Empire State Building in midtown whether I walk, jump in a cab or take the subway. If I have time to kill, I'll take a his, as they take longer than anything for long travels, but great to get to a subway quickly if it's raining.

name: Brand New Beautiful Duplex Apartment with Garden
transit: The G train, Nassau stop, is 1 short block away just around the corner.  The G train travels south into Brooklyn, or north into Queens where you can transfer to the L, E or M into midtown Manhattan. The L train, Bedford Ave. stop, is a 10 minute walk away.  The L train travels into Manhattan 14th St.  1st Ave. and 14th street is one stop away, Union Sq. is 3 stops. The NYC Ferry is a great way to get around, and we live about 15 mins walk from two ferry landings (North Williamsburg and Greenpoint).  For $2.75 you can travel south to Dumbo and explore Brooklyn Bridge Park, or to South Street Seaport, or you can travel north to Queens (LIC and Astoria), East 34th St. in Manhattan, or Roosevelt Island. There is a Citibike (bike share) station across the street. On-street parking is readily available in our neighborhood.

name: Prime Park Slope Townhouse, 4 BR and Garden
transit: Transportation: The area is served by six different subway lines that go into Manhattan and further into Brooklyn. We are a 7-minute walk to the F/G train 7th Avenue station; a 15-minute walk to Grand Army Plaza station where you can catch the 2 or 3 train; a 15-minute walk to the 7th Avenue/Flatbush Avenue stop on the Q or B train. Or, you can travel like a native and avail yourself of Brooklyn’s many bike paths. We are also one short subway stop, or a 30-minute walk, to the Barclays Center and the Brooklyn Academy of Music.

name: Light-filled urban cabin
transit: Just a block and half away is the Franklin subway stop where you can catch the A and the C train.  This subway line zips you into Manhattan (20 minutes to West Village) and connects with many other lines for easy transferring.   Take the A or the C three stops to the Lafayette Ave. stop where you can hop off and explore the lovely neighborhood of Fort Greene.  Enjoy the park and the farmer's market on the weekend.  BAM (Brooklyn Academy of Music) is about a 5 minute walk from the Lafayette stop.  The Barclays Center is about an 8 minute walk.     Take the C three stops to Hoyt-Schermerhorn, you will find yourself in Downtown Brooklyn.  Walk a couple blocks to Atlantic Avenue where you will find boutiques and antique shops.  The Transit Museum is also right here, showing the history of the New York Subway system, including old train cars! name: Luxury Brooklyn brownstone, modern with backyard
transit: Subway Subway line A/C is 12min walk to Utica station and JMZ line is a 14min walk. A/C is a great line to get up to Central Park and Westside of Manhattan, especially since our train stop at Utica runs Express on A train getting you to Manhattan very quickly. J/M train get you to the East Village and Williamsburg, J train runs express in morning & evening so getting to Manhattan door to door is only about 35mins, take the J/M train also to get to Williamsburg quickly. Taxi/Ride Hailing Apps  It only takes about 3-4mins on average for an Uber, Lyft or Juno ride to arrive once your hail it as our area is well frequented. Bus Use (Hidden by Airbnb) Maps to easily plan a route using the bus. You can use your MTA Subway card on the bus. The B46 bus heading north up Malcolm X Blvd will take you to Williamsburg Bridge. Bike Citibike right on our corner, NYC is safer to bike around than you think.

name: Perfect for groups! 3BR, 2Bath feet from Subway!
transit: First, I would suggest downloading the app: Citymapper which is available for iOS and for Android. If you do nothing else before visiting NYC, please download this app! Subway: 116th St Stop on the 2-3 line will take you to Times Square in 4 stops, and will take you all the way downtown in just 32 minutes. There are also the A-C-B-D Lines that are a short walk away as well.  Bus: There are bus stops in our area that will take you crosstown (east-west, west-east).  From Newark:  The fastest way is to take an Uber/Lyft/Via or other car sharing service. You can also take a Taxi but it is very expensive.  For $15.75 and roughly 80 minutes, you can take the Airtrain to Newark Liberty Station, then transfer to a train to New York Penn Station, from there you can ride the 2-3 line from 34th Penn Station 5 STOPS to 116th St and then you will arrive on our street and our co host will be there to meet you once you arrive. name: HARLEM ROCKS/BEST APARtMENT
transit: To get here you can always take a taxi to uptown Manhattan but you may also want to take the subway which is much cheaper.  You may take the 2 or the 3 train Uptown to 125th street Manhattan and walk 3 blocks North going uptown on Malcolm X BLVD/Lenox Avenue to 128TH Street turn right on 128th Street to walk over 2 Avenues all the way to the corner of Madison Avenue. the address 27E I am the building right next to it.   You may also take the M107 Bus to Uptown right on 6th Ave all the way up to 125th Street on Malcolm X BLVD and get out walk 3 blocks North to the corner of 128th Street then walk 2 Avenues over to the corner of Madison and 128th Street. PS: PLEASE PLEASE, do not go to the corner store and tell them that you are Airbnb and you are here to checking in. the store has nothing to do with me and I would like to keep it that way.

name: Winter Escape in Classic Brooklyn Brownstone
transit: As mentioned above, numerous subway lines are just minutes from the house at the 7th Avenue, Bergen St and Atlantic Ave stations (the latter also includes the LIRR commuter rail line). Lower Manhattan is 15-20 minutes away; Greenwich Village is 20-25 mins; Midtown is 30-40 minutes. There is free but scarce street parking so, if you are driving, expect to search, on average, for 10-15 minutes to find a spot. Also note, alternate side of the street parking restrictions require cars be moved 4 times a week. That said, I have successfully parked on the street for 18 years and can offer tips!

name: SHOW STOPPER/BEST APARTMENT IN HARLEM
transit: To get here you can always take a taxi to uptown Manhattan but you may also want to take the subway which is much cheaper.  You may take the 2 or the 3 train Uptown to 125th street Manhattan and walk 3 blocks North going uptown on Malcolm X BLVD/Lenox Avenue to 128TH Street turn right on 128th Street to walk over 2 Avenues all the way to the corner of Madison Avenue. the address 27E I am the building right next to it.   You may also take the M107 Bus to Uptown right on 6th Ave all the way up to 125th Street on Malcolm X BLVD and get out walk 3 blocks North to the corner of 128th Street then walk 2 Avenues over to the corner of Madison and 128th Street. PS: PLEASE PLEASE, do not go to the corner store and tell them that you are Airbnb and you are here to checking in. the store has nothing to do with me and I would like to keep it that way.

name: Luxurious Private Sunny LES Full Floor Loft - NYC
transit: Located 2 minutes walk from the  D, B, F, J, M, Z major train lines.  Recommendation :  Williamsburg Bridge - makes sure you walk across it! This is my favorite bridge in New York for a few reasons: it joins two very cool neighborhoods together - Williamsburg and Lower East Side; it is an outdoor art gallery as it has some great street art to admire as you walk across; the views going into Brooklyn or into Manhattan are spectacular - whether the Empire State is seen or the Domino Sugar Factory. There is a walking lane as well as a bike lane so no collisions will occur when stopping mid-step for that NYC photo opportunity.

name: Spacious Bright Manhattan Home Near The Park
transit: You will be only 3 blocks away from either the 2 & 3 train that takes you up or down the entire West side of Manhattan and all the way to the Bronx or to Brooklyn. You're also 3 blocks to the 6 train which takes you through the entire East side! On Madison and on 5th Ave. several buses (M1, M2, M3, etc) will take you up and down the city for an unsuspected, inexpensive city tour. If you feel like walking you're a couple of steps away from Central Park and all the beautiful strides it offers you. Or just walk down Madison Avenue for some shopping and nice restaurants.  There are also plenty of yellow cabs running day and night on Madison Ave. and 5th Ave.  Plus the clever option of Uber, Juno and Lyft.

name: Luxury redefined: Splendid sleep in the skies
transit: There's a public garage in the building with direct access from the lobby. A daily, weekly and/or monthly charge applies that you will be responsible to cover.  Although the simplest way to commute in NYC is via Uber/Lyft, taxicabs and/or subway.  The subway is only a few steps away from the building (42nd Street/Port Authority station). It is one of NYC’s most central subway stations where you can access almost every single line!   Commute from and to all 3 major NYC airports directly from this spot: approx. 40 minutes to LaGuardia Airport and 57 minutes to JFK and Newark airports.  And if you plan to go to Woodbury commons outlet, one of the US’s most elaborate outlet malls, there’s a daily bus service (almost every hour) from this same location that can take you there and bring you back. name: Trendy Apartment In Soho / LES Neighborhood
transit: Subway: The F train and J, M, Z trains are just 2-3 blocks away. The B, D is about 5 blocks away (7-min walk). 4,6 and N, Q, R are about a 10-min walk away. Bus: Buses are located all around the condo. There are plenty of buses that take you across cross-town or up / down-town Cabs: You’ll find an empty cab every 5 seconds on E Houston Street just around the corner Airport: If you’re coming from the airport, your best bet is a cab or an Uber. It should cost around $30-$50 and take 30-40 mins from JFK or LaGuardia. Ferry: There is a ferry commuter terminal on 35th & East River if you want to take a nice scenic boat ride to other locations in downtown Manhattan, Long Island City and Brooklyn.

transit: Located midway between JFK or LGA Airport and Manhattan (30 minutes each way), just two short blocks from the J train at the Halsey stop, guests also have the option of taking the A, C, L, and Z trains all within a short walk.  (Hidden by Airbnb) Maps has all the subways, buses, and public transit and is the best way to get directions. In addition, NYC has its own transit app called myMTA that is invaluable in figuring out how to get around in real-time. We also highly recommend the Uber/Lyft/ Juno ride share services, an inexpensive way to call a car anytime, anywhere in NYC.   There is also alternate side street parking for those who want to drive. Bike rentals are also a popular option and there is a place close by.

name: Big 3 Bedroom Apartment in Prime Midtown Manhatten
transit: Public transportation is very accessible with the closest train station being about an 8 minute walk away. The nearest station is 33rd Street Station and trains 4,5,6 run from there. City Bike stations are nearby. To see the location simply download the city bike app on almost any smartphone. Ferry's also leave from 34th street, making it very easy to get to Brooklyn, long island city and more. (the ferry is $2.75 or free depending on what one you ride. There are also bus stops within minutes walking distance from our apartment. Bus routes and locations can be found on (Hidden by Airbnb) or apple maps. Walking is also always an option considering our space is located right in the middle of the city.
